# Project Coding Style

## Core Principles

- Keep code simple and human-readable.
- Avoid over-engineering and deep abstraction.
- Do not create unnecessary generic utility layers.
- Use clear, descriptive file names and identifiers.
- Prefer explicit typing over implicit or vague types.

## Architecture and Boundaries

- Keep controller/service separation practical and direct.
- Add abstractions only when they clearly reduce complexity.
- Solve the current problem well; do not build speculative frameworks.

## Comments and Documentation

- Add comments only where intent is not obvious from code.
- Keep comments short and focused on *why*, not *what*.

## Production Expectations

- Keep code production-friendly, but still easy to understand and maintain.
- Prefer predictable behavior, clear error handling, and straightforward control flow.
